\strong{Why it matters.} Each timed transition sets a fresh duration timer when an
agent \emph{enters} a state, and the step for the \emph{next} transition decrements that
timer. If the inflow step runs before the outflow step within the same tick, a
just-arrived agent is decremented immediately and loses one tick of residency —
its effective exposed or infectious period becomes \code{duration - 1} rather than
\code{duration}. Running downstream-first prevents this: a newly exposed or
infectious agent is not touched again until the next tick.

\strong{SIR caveat.} For direct S -> I transmission a one-tick offset persists
regardless of order. An agent becomes infectious \emph{inside}
\code{\link[=step_transmission_si]{step_transmission_si()}}, after that step has already computed its infectious
tally, so it first contributes to the force of infection on the \emph{next} tick.
The SIR effective basic reproduction number is therefore \code{beta * (D - 1)},
whereas SEIR — where agents enter \code{I} via the separate \code{\link[=step_exposed_ei]{step_exposed_ei()}},
which runs before the transmission tally — yields the full \code{beta * D}.

The \code{sir_attack_fraction.R} and \code{seir_attack_fraction.R} scripts in the
package's \verb{examples/} directory demonstrate both, validating the simulated
attack fraction against the Kermack-McKendrick final-size relation.
